{
  "genre": "reggae",
  "mode": "relaxation",
  "mixStrategy": "This relaxation reggae arrangement uses three tracks occupying distinct frequency bands to create a warm, spacious island feel. BASS (Electric Bass, 20-300Hz): The foundation locks into a classic reggae dotted-quarter pattern, playing root notes and 5ths of each chord with long sustains. It sits deep in the E1-E3 range, providing warmth and weight. CHORDS (Organ, 300Hz-2kHz): The iconic reggae offbeat skank \u2014 silent on every downbeat, hitting on the 'and' of each beat. Voiced in the C4-C6 range, the organ chords provide harmonic body and the characteristic reggae rhythmic pulse. MELODY (Nylon Guitar, 1kHz-8kHz): A gentle, singable melody in the C4-C5 range that floats above the rhythm section. It plays chord tones on strong beats and uses passing scale tones on weak beats, with moderate sustains for a relaxed feel. RHYTHMIC INTERLOCK: Bass plays on downbeats with long sustains, organ hits on upbeats creating the offbeat skank, and melody weaves between them with longer phrases. This creates the classic reggae push-pull feel. ENERGY ARC: Segments 1(0-7.5s)=0.3 sparse entry, 2(7.5-15s)=0.5 building, 3(15-22.5s)=0.6 gentle peak, 4(22.5-30s)=0.7 fullest energy, 5(30-37.5s)=0.6 easing, 6(37.5-45s)=0.4 gentle fade. CHORD PROGRESSION: I(C) \u2192 V(G) \u2192 vi(Am) \u2192 IV(F), repeating every ~6.5 bars (~25.6s), with all tracks changing chords together. The quarter note = 0.984s, so half note = 1.968s, whole note = 3.936s. Upbeats fall at +0.492s from each beat.",
